actions.comment:
This issue is still relevant in the current codebase. The root cause is confirmed: `GLTextureView` (which replaced `GLSurfaceView` in v1.60.1) does not call `eglSwapInterval`, so the render loop runs uncapped when using `Rendermode.Continuously`.

Here's a workaround you can use: switch to `Rendermode.WhenDirty` and drive rendering from a timer at your target frame rate:

```csharp
// Set the view to only render on demand
skglView.RenderMode = Rendermode.WhenDirty;

// Timer-based invalidation at ~60 FPS
// Store timer as a field and dispose on cleanup
var timer = new System.Timers.Timer(16.67);
timer.Elapsed += (s, e) => skglView.RequestRender();
timer.Start();

// In cleanup/Dispose:
// timer.Stop();
// timer.Dispose();
```

**Note:** On Android, `Android.OS.Handler` or `View.PostDelayed()` may be more reliable than `System.Timers.Timer` for frame timing. Be sure to call `OnPause()`/`OnResume()` for proper lifecycle management.

For animation correctness regardless of frame rate, use delta-time (initialize `lastFrame` to avoid a large first-frame delta):

```csharp
var sw = Stopwatch.StartNew();
var lastFrame = sw.Elapsed;

void OnPaint(object sender, SKPaintGLSurfaceEventArgs e)
{
    var now = sw.Elapsed;
    var deltaTime = (now - lastFrame).TotalSeconds;
    lastFrame = now;
    position += velocity * (float)deltaTime;
}
```

A proper engine-level fix would involve either adding `eglSwapInterval(1)` to the EGL setup, or integrating Android's Choreographer API for display-synced rendering. Both approaches have tradeoffs around whether VSync should be default or opt-in.
